IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDescription: JANUS YOUTH PROGRAMS HAS BEEN CHANGING LIVES AND BUILDING FUTURES FOR CHILDREN, YOUTH, AND FAMILIES IN OREGON AND WASHINGTON SINCE 1972.FROM RESIDENTIAL TREATMENT PROGRAMS, THE NORTHWEST'S LARGEST ARRAY OF RUNAWAY AND HOMELESS YOUTH SERVICES, ALTERNATIVE EDUCATION CLASSROOMS, A DETENTION PROGRAM, A TEEN PARENTING PROGRAM, A COLLEGE SCHOLARSHIP PROGRAM, AND A 85,000 SQUARE FOOT URBAN AGRICULTURE PROGRAM ADDRESSING HUNGER AND EMPLOYMENT ISSUES, JANUS IS COMMITTED TO DELIVERING INNOVATIVE COMMUNITY-BASED PROGRAMS.REACHING NEARLY 36,000 CHILDREN, YOUTH, AND FAMILIES YEARLY, JANUS YOUTH PROGRAMS IS ONE OF THE LARGEST NONPROFITS IN THE NORTHWEST COMMITTED TO DELIVERING PROGRAMS THAT CHANGE LIVES AND BUILD FUTURES.
IRS990.MissionDescription: Janus Youth Programs is a leader in creating innovative, community-based services which enhance the quality of life for children, youth, and families. We work in partnership with others to create a safe and healthy community.
IRS990.Description: Residential services - Five long and short-term residential and shelter programs that provide mental health services and specialized treatment and care for males and females aged 12 to 24 who are in state custody, either through the Oregon Department of Human Services or the Oregon Youth Authority. The long-term goal is to facilitate a successful return to home and family or to independent living in the community.

Activity2.Description: Homeless Youth Services - Extensive array of homeless youth programs including street outreach, assessment, emergency and short-term shelter, transitional and independent living options, and alcohol and drug services designed to assist homeless youth to successfully exit street life.

Activity3.Description: Runaway Youth Services - Temporary shelter and family crisis intervention services for runaway youth designed to facilitate a return to home or alternative community setting, and to provide linkage with ongoing follow-up services. Additional programmatic service includes operation of the Reception Center which offers law enforcement an alternative to a locked setting for youth with curfew violations, active runaway reports, and misdemeanors.

ActivityOther.Description: Insights Teen Parent Programs - An array of services provided to young parents and pregnant teenagers including case management, parenting education/support groups, safe supervised apartment living, and support to attend and complete high school, obtain a GED, or work toward employment.

Education services - Educational services are provided through three programs including a private, 40-seat alternative education school serving boys and girls who have been unsuccessful in public schools and/or who have a need for special education services, an alternative education program in a public high school designed specifically for youth in residential treatment, and a self-contained, on-campus school at the Janus residential program in Washington County.

Urban Agriculture Program - An 85,000 square foot urban agriculture program that includes community organic gardens, an orchard, and a one-acre youth-run entrepreneurial farm on Sauvie Island addressing hunger, employment, and community health issues in three North Portland public housing developments. The program also includes after-school homework clubs, mentoring opportunities, and year-round educational opportunities for children.

Form990ScheduleJPartIII.Explanation: The Executive Director bonus is considered part of his employment contract. A lump sum amount is paid annually based on a performance review by Fiscal and Executive Committees. Bonuses to other staff are based upon individual situations where the employee either has worked substantial extra time over an extended period or has had extra job duties assigned over an extended time or has demonstrated extraordinary performance beyond normal job expectations.

Line 25 "Other" contributions of $343,815 consist of construction-related contributions (i.e. materials and services) solicited by the Home Builders Foundation of Metropolitan Portland, a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization doing business as "HomeAid Portland."

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 11
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: The form 990 is prepared by an independent CPA, reviewed by the finance manager and the executive and/or finance committee, and then given to the board of directors prior to filing.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 12c
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: Upon acceptance to the board, members are given a conflict of interest policy and required to disclose any potential conflicts. Periodically the policy is discussed. Potential conflicts are then monitored and when voting actions occur in board meetings, any person known to have a conflict of interest is excused from the meeting until the discussion and vote is completed, and such excusals are documented in the minutes.

Form 990, Part VI, Section B, Line 15a: The executive committee of the board of directors determines executive director and officer compensation after conducting formal performance reviews and surveying compensation levels for executive directors and officers of other 501(c)(3) organizations in the state of Oregon.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section C, line 19
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: The organization makes its governing documents, conflict of interest policy, and financial statements available to the public upon request.
